{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fb46f3a9-62b6-4818-ab06-8d1b60a2c13b","content":"\n\n`SafeAreaEdges` alone doesn't make content draw behind system bars on both platforms. You likely need a combination of these:\n\n**1. Hide Shell chrome** (if using `Shell`):\n```xml\n<ContentPage ...\n    Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n    Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n```\n\n**2. iOS — disable safe area insets:**\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\nios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n```\n\n**3. Android — enter immersive full-screen mode** (platform-specific code in your page's code-behind or handler):\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nprotected override void OnAppearing()\n{\n    base.OnAppearing();\n    var activity = Platform.CurrentActivity;\n    var window = activity.Window;\n    var controller = AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat\n        .GetInsetsController(window, window.DecorView);\n    controller.Hide(AndroidX.Core.View.WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n    controller.SystemBarsBehavior =\n        AndroidX.Core.View.WindowInsetsControllerCompat.BehaviorShowTransientBarsBySwipe;\n}\n#endif\n```\n\n**4. Image setup:**\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nThe key insight: on **iOS**, `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` lets the layout extend behind notch/home indicator. On **Android**, the system bars are separate OS-level chrome — you must use `WindowInsetsController` to hide them (or make them transparent). `SafeAreaEdges` alone doesn't trigger either of these platform behaviors.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ba39d70-7688-4c47-84e1-d69c30252d17","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI edge-to-edge display for a photo viewer. This is a common issue in .NET MAUI, especially with .NET 10 which introduced changes to edge-to-edge behavior on Android.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, starting with .NET 10 (and Android 15+), Android apps run edge-to-edge by default. However, simply setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on a `ContentPage` isn't sufficient to make content draw behind system bars. Here's what's needed:\n\n1. **`IgnoreSafeArea`** on the specific view (the `Image` control) — this is key. The `SafeAreaEdges` property on `ContentPage` controls which edges the page's content area respects, but the actual view needs `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` to extend behind system bars.\n\n\n2. On Android with .NET 10, I need to ensure the system bars are transparent and that the window doesn't fit system windows — the platform-specific configuration is crucial for making the content actually extend edge-to-edge. On iOS, I'd use `UseSafeArea=\"false\"` to achieve similar behavior, but Android requires different handling through window configuration.\n\nFor MAUI specifically, the `IgnoreSafeArea` property on views is what controls whether individual elements respect safe area insets, though the window-level configuration on Android is what actually enables the edge-to-edge layout in the first place. Looking at what the user actually needs for a full-screen photo viewer, the real solution involves disabling safe area handling on iOS with the platform-specific attribute, then ensuring the image stretches across the entire viewport with proper aspect ratio. On Android, I need to enable edge-to-edge rendering by configuring the window insets and making the system bars transparent so content can draw behind them.\n\nSetting up Android platform code... I'm narrowing down the practical solution: hiding Shell chrome with `NavBarIsVisible` and `TabBarIsVisible`, disabling safe area on iOS, and enabling full-screen mode on Android, then letting an image with `AspectFill` fill the entire page. I should focus on what's likely causing the issue in .NET 10 MAUI rather than getting caught up in preview-version specifics, since the core problem remains the same—the layout needs to respect neither safe areas nor system bar padding.","outputTokens":2173},"id":"d47b17f8-e6a2-4ed9-be3e-6b0c6246e865","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:50:52.696Z","parentId":"d524f840-4517-4283-b5c4-d45572268231"}
